<div id="review_90542528" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/90542528" />
    <a title="Kathleen Hagen" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1291703-kathleen-hagen"><img alt="Kathleen Hagen" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/90542528?book_show_action=true">Feb 20, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kathleen Hagen" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kathleen Hagen" href="/user/show/1291703-kathleen-hagen">Kathleen Hagen</a>
      </span>

          added it


          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781586487072" href="/book/show/6457760-my-guantanamo-diary">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1291703-kathleen-hagen?shelf=2010-audio-books">2010-audio-books</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1291703-kathleen-hagen?shelf=2010-nonfiction">2010-nonfiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer90542528" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14965849357975654557">My Guantanamo Diaries, by Mahvish Rukhsana Khan, produced by Audible inc. narrated by Shelley Johnson, downloaded from audible.com.<br/><br/>The narrator wasn’t right for this book. Her voice was too light and chatty a lot of the time for the serious nature of this book. The author was a third-year law student who attached herself to the Habeas Corpus project of lawyers working full-time on getting trials for persons held at Guatanamo camp, some of who were there for three or four years by the time she ca</span>
  <span id="freeText14965849357975654557" style="display:none">My Guantanamo Diaries, by Mahvish Rukhsana Khan, produced by Audible inc. narrated by Shelley Johnson, downloaded from audible.com.<br /><br />The narrator wasn’t right for this book. Her voice was too light and chatty a lot of the time for the serious nature of this book. The author was a third-year law student who attached herself to the Habeas Corpus project of lawyers working full-time on getting trials for persons held at Guatanamo camp, some of who were there for three or four years by the time she came. The author was from a second generation family from Afghanistan and knew some of the dialects, and therefore acted as an interpreter. She wrote about being introduced to the detainees, having them be suspicious initially of the lawyers-after all why would American lawyers come to help people considered enemies of America-and everyone, the author included, came in for very nosey questions about their own lives. She recorded the stories of abuse she heard from them, and finally even went to Afghanistan to track down people from some of their families to get character witnesses and to get evidence of the businesses they ran and that they weren’t enemies. While some of the detainees had become very angry with the U.S. because of the way they had been treated, others were more angry with fellow countrymen in Afghanistan and Pakistan, because actually many of them acted as bounty hunters, rounding up people that were their own personal enemies and selling them to the Americans as terrorists. This was an intense and riveting book. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="14965849357975654557" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


