<div id="review_159697248" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/159697248" />
    <a title="Edina Truth-Jones" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/641657-edina-truth-jones"><img alt="Edina Truth-Jones" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1445766970p2/641657.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/159697248?book_show_action=true">Apr 08, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Edina Truth-Jones" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Edina Truth-Jones" href="/user/show/641657-edina-truth-jones">Edina Truth-Jones</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer159697248" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2523331933163927493">This book captures the the wrongful arrests of innocent people by the U.S., the abuse, the violations, the disgusting and horrendous torture committed in the name of &quot;War on Terror.&quot; What makes this even a more depressing account is that Mahvish was only able to write about a few prisoners. There are hundreds like them in Gitmo and most have endured atrocities committed against them.<br/><br/>It is clear that U.S. had an agenda to fulfill and it is clear that they were going to accomplish that goal by cre</span>
  <span id="freeText2523331933163927493" style="display:none">This book captures the the wrongful arrests of innocent people by the U.S., the abuse, the violations, the disgusting and horrendous torture committed in the name of "War on Terror." What makes this even a more depressing account is that Mahvish was only able to write about a few prisoners. There are hundreds like them in Gitmo and most have endured atrocities committed against them.<br /><br />It is clear that U.S. had an agenda to fulfill and it is clear that they were going to accomplish that goal by creating lies and false accusations. It is clear that no true investigations took place to prove that these men that are being tortured daily are actually guilty. In most cases, no evidence was found against them. The arrests started when the DEpartment of Defense started dropping bounty leaflets, which offered $5,000 - $25,000 to anyone bringing in "people of interest" to the U.S. It's devastating to read about men sold into captivity by their own country men. The Pakistani particularly offended me with their decisions to aid the U.S. in wrongful arrests.<br /><br />Overall the book caused emotional disturbance and I have cried through a lot of the parts, especially when detailed information of the extent of torture committed against the prisoners was present. My mind does not have the ability to grasp how one can commit such abominable and cruel acts.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="2523331933163927493" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


